<font color="#FF0000">FAMILY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27  9:39:34 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I never expected to be affected by my visit to the Wall in the way I was.  My cousin (Larry Johnson) had been killed in Vietnam in 1969, and even then I questioned our involvement in the war.  My sister and I believed that our cousin was not really dead, and that 10 years later or so he would show up at my aunt's front door like some '70s movie of the week. Well he hasn't showed up yet.  Although he was a bit older than me, I remember being struck deeply by this loss; perhaps it was because it's one of only two times I ever saw my father cry.<br><br>
I was a bit resistant about visiting the wall because I thought it might somehow glorify our actions in Vietnam, which is how most war memorials affect me. However, I didn't know when I'd have the chance again, so after visiting the Holocaust Museum, we headed down to see the wall.  <br><br>
Walking along the wall, it really hit home to me exactly how many Americans besides my cousin died in Vietnam.  At the begining the wall is very small - only a few names.  As  I reached the center where Larry's name was, the wall was way over my head.  His name is in line 40 and I could barely reach up and touch it.  My realization was that this many mothers, fathers, sisters and brothers, cousins, aunts and uncles experienced the same pain and loss as I did in 1969 - a strangely unifying event for me.  <br><br>
In some respects I think we should build walls like this with every military engagement we are involved in (Gulf War, Bosnia, Somalia) so the American people can see how many lives are being lost - and for what?<br><br>
Walking away, I thought that we maybe need another Vietnam Wall - one that details the incredible affect on the lives of the people who fought there and lived.  I know of so many men who are still dealing with the affects of this event in their lives - they will never be the same.  How could they?  How do we honor their pain and struggle, which continues on 20+ hears later?<br><br>

